				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varPhi = E_{\text{vacuum}} - E_{\text{Fermi}}$$\end{document}where Evacuum and EFermi are the energy of an electron at the stationary point in the vacuum in line with the surface and Fermi level, respectively.

For any newly formed semiconductor to be considered as valuable for photovoltaic activity, ideally, the bandgap must be within 1.1–1.5 eV range to enhance the solar absorption energy. Effective charge separation and optical absorption are also influential in photovoltaic performance [80]. Based on the obtained optical absorption results, there is a promising enhancement for visible light for the photovoltaic activity of GaS/C2N heterostructure as compared to the individual materials. The improved photovoltaic activity affected by the efficient separation and transfer of photogenerated electrons depends heavily on the band structures of the individual parts [81]. The GaS/C2N heterostructure is assessed by analysing the band position of the valence band and conduction band in relation to the photoexcited electrons of the formed heterostructure. The VBM and CBM of GaS/C2N heterostructure are evaluated from the respective bandgaps of the individual components and their absolute electronegativity of atoms using the empirical equations:4EVB=X-Ee+0.5Eg\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
